Relation between cognitive function and mortality in middle-aged adults: the 
atherosclerosis risk in communities study.

Pavlik VN(1), de Moraes SA, Szklo M, Knopman DS, Mosley TH Jr, Hyman DJ.

Author information:
(1)Department of Family and Community Medicine, Baylor College of Medicine, 
Houston, TX 77005, USA. vpavlik@bcm.tmc.edu

An independent, inverse association between cognitive function and all-cause 
mortality has been reported in elderly cohorts. The purpose of this study was to 
determine whether the same association exists in middle-aged persons. The 
Atherosclerosis Risk in Communities Study is a cohort study initiated in 1987 to 
investigate the development of atherosclerosis in middle-aged persons. Three 
cognitive function measures were included in the second cohort examination 
conducted from 1990 to 1992 when the participants were aged 48-67 years: the 
Delayed Word Recall Test (DWRT), the Digit Symbol Substitution Test (DSST) (a 
subtest from the Wechsler Adult Intelligence Scale-Revised), and the Word 
Fluency Test from the Multilingual Aphasia Examination. Cox proportional hazards 
modeling was used to determine whether all-cause mortality ascertained through 
1997 was associated with each measure after adjustment for sociodemographic, 
biologic, psychologic, and behavioral risk factors. Without adjustment, there 
was a significantly lower mortality hazard associated with higher scores on all 
three measures. After covariate adjustment, the hazard ratios for the DWRT and 
the DSST remained significant (hazard ratio1-point DWRT score increment = 0.90, 
95% confidence interval: 0.84, 0.97; hazard ratio 7-point DSST score increment = 
0.86, 95% confidence interval: 0.80, 0.93). Cognitive function measured in 
middle age appears to have prognostic importance for life expectancy similar to 
that reported in elderly adults.

