OBJECTIVES: To assess the effect of nocturia on productivity, vitality and 
utility in a selected group of professionally active individuals with nocturia, 
compared with matched controls, and investigate the effect of symptom severity, 
to test the hypothesis that lack of sleep caused by frequent sleep interruptions 
could reduce an individuals' daytime energy and activity levels.
SUBJECTS AND METHODS: Subjects (203) were recruited in Sweden through 
advertisements, and their suitability for the study assessed in a structured 
interview. Controls (80) matched for age and gender were randomly selected from 
